## Conditionally Rendering

1. Rendering means printing or displaying.
2. In HTTP you can only print text, it can be an HTML Text, CSS Text, JSON Text, Javascript Test.
3. Basically it means generating strings dynamically.
4. Conditional rendering is what makes your website interactive.


### There are 2 ways of writing conditions:  

Using the `if....else`  statement.  

```js
let canDrive = false;
if(age > 16){
    // do something
    canDrive = true;
}
else{
    canDrive = false;
}
```
Or using a ternary (the most popular for conditional rendering):

```js
let canDrive = (age > 16) ? true : false;
```
Note: as you can see the ternary is smaller, it's a great and agile resource.

## What is conditional rendering?

It means using conditions to generate HTML dynamically. Basically, your HTML will be different depending on certain **conditions** that you determine.

For example, using the same condition before:
```js
let canDrive = (age > 16) ? "can" : "cannot";
let myHTML = 'I ' + canDrive + " drive";

// myHTML will be either "I can drive" or "I cannot drive"
```

With the javascript template literrals is even easier to generate strings dynamically.

```js

let person = {
    name: "Alejandro",
    age: 17
}
let myHTML = `
    <div>
          <p>My name is ${person.name}</p>
          <p>and I am ${person.age > 21 ? "capable" : "not capable"} to drink</p>
    </div>
`;
```
This javascript code will output the following HTML:

```html
    <div>
          <p>My name is Alejandro</p>
          <p>and I am capable to drink</p>
    </div>
```

